<HEAD>Defection Of Hindu Fundamentalist Party Threatens Singh Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A right-wing Hindu party withdrew its
support for Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>'s government today,
threatening to bring down the fragile coalition that has governed
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> for the past 10 months.
   Singh refused to resign and said he would take the battle to
floor of <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, where his centrist <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> government
had relied on the votes of the Hindu fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya
Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> to survive.
   The crisis was precipitated by the arrest earlier <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> of
<ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata</ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON>Lal Krishna Advani</PERSON>, as he led a
cross-country march to muster support for building a new Hindu
temple on the site of a <DATE>16th century</DATE> Moslem mosque.
   About six hours later, party leaders submitted a letter to
Indian President <PERSON>Ramaswamy Venkataraman</PERSON> withdrawing support for
<ORGANIZATION>Singh's National Front</ORGANIZATION> government.
   The prime minister told reporters at the presidential palace
that the loss of Bharatiya Janata support ``doesn't mean that all
support is gone.'' However, it was unclear how he could avoid
calling new elections.
   With the defection of the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s
centrist government loses the fragile majority it cobbled together
from across the political spectrum after <DATE>November</DATE> general
elections.
   No single party had won enough seats to take power unilaterally.
   The next steps are up to <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> and the president.
   Under the constitution, the options include <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s resignation
as prime minister and elections for a new Parliament.
   President <PERSON>Venkataraman</PERSON> could also ask Singh to try to muster a
new majority in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, which appears mathematically and
politically improbable.
   Or, the president can turn to the opposition leader, former
Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>, and ask if <ORGANIZATION>Gandhi</ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>
could form a coalition government.
   That also appears unlikely.
   The crisis was precipitated by <PERSON>Advani</PERSON>'s determination to go
ahead with his march to bolster support for the campaign to replace
a Moslem mosque with a temple to the Hindu god <ORGANIZATION>Lord Rama</ORGANIZATION>.
   Singh had urged Hindu fundamentalists to postpone the temple
plan. At least 80 people died this month in Hindu-Moslem clashes
spurred by the dispute.
   In a nationally televised address <DATE>Monday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> renewed
his appeal and said he was prepared to face the fact that his stand
could bring down the government.
   ``Religious fanaticism is the first step towards the foundation
for a theocratic state,'' <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> said in his 20-minute TV speech.
``It will be the death of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> as a secular state.''
   The prime minister added: ``Hundreds of governments can come and
go, but the nation should remain one.''
   Advani was arrested about sunrise in a remote part of <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION>
state near the village of Samastipur, about 450 miles southeast of
<LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   He had been leading a caravan of supporters across the Hindu
heartland to demonstrate and bolster support for plans to build a
temple on a site now occupied by a 16th century mosque in the holy
Hindu town of <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>. Ayodhya is in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh state</LOCATION>, which
lies between <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION> state.
   Advani's planned path through <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Uttar Pradesh</PERSON> en route
to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> would have taken him through poor villages populated by
both Moslems and Hindus. In <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION> especially, these villages have
been recurring flashpoints for Hindu-Moslem violence.
   Hindu fundamentalists have vowed to start building the temple in
one week on the spot where they say the Hindu god <ORGANIZATION>Lord Rama</ORGANIZATION> was
born. Moslem activists and religious leaders have vowed to prevent
any encroachment on the mosque.
   The outcry has torn at the social and political fabric of
officially secular <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>, where <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of the 880 million
people are Hindus. Moslems form <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of the population.
   Singh took office in <DATE>December</DATE> after ousting <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and his
<ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> in the <DATE>November</DATE> general election. Although the
<ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> and its allies hold 210 of <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>'s 522 seats,
it lacked the majority to govern.
   Singh's <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> coalition holds just 141 seats, but it
won the tacit support of the two extremes of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s political
spectrum: <PERSON>Advani</PERSON>'s right-wing Hindu party and the Left Front
alliance of several communist parties.
   With that support, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> could draw on enough votes to give him
the majority needed to pass legislation and stay in power.
   Bharatiya Janata has 88 members of <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION>, the Left Front
51.
</TEXT>
