<HEAD>Fundamentalist Hindus Defer Plan to Build Disputed Temple</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fundamentalist Hindus decided <DATE>Friday</DATE> to
postpone building a temple at a disputed religious site claimed by
both Moslems and Hindus.
   Avaidyanath, a Hindu priest who uses one name, told reporters
the <ORGANIZATION>World Hindu Conference</ORGANIZATION> decided to postpone construction of the
temple for at least four months so the government can find a
solution to the long-running dispute.
   Construction was to have started <DATE>Feb. 14</DATE> on land that also
contains a 16th century mosque.
   Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON> said building the shrine would inflame
religious passions and lead to widespread violence, and he urged
Hindus to call off construction.
   ``We have decided to accept the prime minister's appeal,'' said
<PERSON>Avaidyanath</PERSON>, who wore the saffron robes of a Hindu ascetic. ``We'll
give him four months to solve the issue.''
   Last year, at least 300 people died in violence sparked by the
Hindu group's decision to build the temple and raze the mosque. The
foundation stone for the shrine was laid <DATE>Nov. 9</DATE>, but construction
was postponed because of the dispute.
   Hindus claim the site is the birthplace of the <ORGANIZATION>Rama</ORGANIZATION>, an
incarnation of <LOCATION>Vishnu</LOCATION>, one of the most important Hindu gods. They
say the Babri Masjid, or the mosque named after <PERSON>Moghal</PERSON> emperor
<PERSON>Babar</PERSON>, was built over <LOCATION>Rama</LOCATION>'s birthplace.
   Moslems say it is difficult to say where Rama was born and they
will not accept destruction of their mosque.
   The issue has become a flashpoint for tensions between <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s
majority Hindus, who make up <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of its 880 million people,
and its Moslems, who form the country's largest minority but still
comprise only <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of the population.
   The dispute became a major issue in last <DATE>November</DATE>'s general
elections, and analysts say it was one of the causes of the
downfall of the previous prime minister, <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>.
   Singh, his successor, has not come up with any specfic plan to
solve the problem but has promised to set up a government committee
to meet Hindu and Moslem representatves and try to come up with a
solution.
   ``The problem has been hanging for 450 years,'' said <PERSON>Ashok
Singhal</PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION>World Hindu Conference</ORGANIZATION>. ``Four
months more will not matter.''
</TEXT>
