<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Hindu holy men and their
followers broke through police barricades <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> and stormed
toward the Moslem mosque they want to replace with a Hindu temple.
   Many were beaten back by police who fired tear gas and lashed
out with iron-tipped bamboo canes. Dozens were injured. Hindu holy
men screamed obscenities from rooftops and pelted the police with
stones.
   About 200 people overran police lines in the narrow lanes and
were halted at the foot of the hill just 600 feet from the mosque.
   The religious dispute has made the name of this Hindu holy town
a battle cry in Moslem-Hindu riots that have left more than 100
dead across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in the past week.
   The dispute threatens to topple the government of Prime Minister
<PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>. A right-wing Hindu party withdrew its support for Singh
last week when his government tried to deter plans to build new
Hindu temple where the mosque now stands.
   Ayodhya had been under around-the-clock curfew since <DATE>Friday</DATE> in
an effort to keep Hindu fundamentalists from carrying out their vow
to begin construction of the temple <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>.
   Roads leading to the <DATE>16th century</DATE> mosque were blocked, but about
5,000 people emerged from hiding places in fields around <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>
before sunrise and stormed a bridge leading into the town.
   Police arrested between 100 and 200 people and rained blows with
their bamboo canes on fallen members of the crowd. The 600
policemen on the mile-long bridge eventually turned back the crowd.
   Inside <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, a town of about 40,000 people, reporters saw
some members of the state police force lift barricades and let
Hindu holy men run into the lanes leading to the mosque. The
infiltrators were halted short of the mosque by federal
paramilitary police.
   On <DATE>Monday</DATE>, a group of about 80 Hindu holy men in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> threw
stones at police and set a bus on fire when authorities attempted
to arrest a local Hindu priest, a police inspector said.
   The inspector, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it was
an isolated incident and did not cause any lasting tension.
   But within an hour of the skirmish, authorities banned entry
into <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> and canceled passes issued to reporters.
   Despite the efforts to deter them and the presence of 20,000
police and paramilitary troops in town, the Hindu fundamentalists
vowed to start the temple construction program as scheduled.
   In <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>World Hindu Council</ORGANIZATION> had claimed
10,000 supporters had slipped through police cordons and roadblocks
around <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   The exact time for the start of construction has not been
announced.
   In <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, Prime Minister Singh offered to resign if the
Hindu fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, which supports the
temple construction program, would accept a legal verdict on the
dispute.
   Singh's <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> coalition was relegated to a minority in
<LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> <DATE>last week</DATE> after Bharatiya Janata withdrew its support to
the government. Singh has maintained he still holds a parliamentary
majority and is scheduled to seek a vote of confidence on <DATE>Nov. 7</DATE>.
   The government has vowed to block the temple construction and
said a court of law should decide who the site belongs to.
   The fundamentalists claim the mosque stands atop the very spot
where Rama, one of the most worshipped Hindu gods, was born and
therefore is a religious matter, not a legal one.
   Moslems, a minority in officially secular but predominantly
<LOCATION>Hindu India</LOCATION>, fear the displacement of one mosque could jeopardize
hundreds of other Islamic sites across the country.
   On <DATE>Friday</DATE> the government of Uttar Pradesh state imposed an
around-the-clock curfew in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> in an effort to keep temple
advocates from reaching the disputed hilltop. Trains to the area
were halted and roads blocked by police and paramilitary troops.
   Moslems make up <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people, of
whom <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> are Hindu. In <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh state</LOCATION>, where the
government is allied with <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>, Moslems account for about <PERCENT>30
percent</PERCENT> of the 120 million people.
</TEXT>
