<UNK>Magistrate Blocks Hindu Construction at Site Claimed by Moslems</UNK>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district magistrate on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> blocked
construction of a Hindu temple that has ignited violent protests by
Moslems who claim the project infringes on their holy land, a news
agency said.
   Press Trust of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> said the fundamentalist Hindu group trying
to build the temple at <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 325 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>,
had agred to delay construction pending discussions at a religious
convocation in <DATE>January</DATE>.
   At least 300 people have been killed in Hindu-Moslem riots in
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION> since mid-August, when the World Conference of Hindus vowed
to build the temple on a site occupied by a 16th century mosque.
   The foundation of the new temple was placed <DATE>Friday</DATE> about 120
feet in front of the Babri Masjid mosque, whose name honors <PERSON>Babar</PERSON>,
one of the Mogul conquerors who introduced Islam to <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   The ceremony touched off attacks on Hindu temples and shops
<DATE>Saturday</DATE> in two neighboring Moslem nations: <LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, which were part of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> before <DATE>1947</DATE> when the former
British-ruled subcontinent was partitioned along religious lines
into independent nations.
   More protests erupted <DATE>Sunday</DATE>. In <LOCATION>Lahore</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>, hundreds of
Pakistanis lined a major street, chanting slogans and rattling
placards in opposition to the temple.
   Moslems and Hindus both claim the temple site is sacred to their
religion. Hindus say the mosque was built atop an ancient Hindu
temple marking the birthplace of <ORGANIZATION>Lord Ram</ORGANIZATION>, one of the most popular
gods in the Hindu pantheon.
   The area's district magistrate, <PERSON>R.S. Srivastava</PERSON>, was quoted
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> by Press Trust of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> as saying he could not give the
Hindus permission to continue digging at the site as long as the
matter was pending in court.
   Press Trust said the Hindu group building the temple, <ORGANIZATION>Vishwa
Hindu Parishad</ORGANIZATION>, had agreed to halt work temporarily.
   It quoted the group's general secretary, <PERSON>Ashok Singhal</PERSON>, as
saying a decision on the next course of action would be made during
a Hindu conference in <LOCATION>Allahabad</LOCATION> on <DATE>Jan. 27</DATE>.
   <PERSON>Singhal</PERSON> said last week his group would not try to demolish the
mosque but wanted to remove it ``intact and honorably'' from the
site.
   Moslems say this would set a bad precedent, since they say there
are at least 316 other mosques in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> that Hindus claim are built
on Hindu holy places.
   Pakistani Prime Minister <PERSON>Benazir Bhutto</PERSON> on <DATE>Saturday</DATE> denounced
the planned temple as ``a willful desecration of an Islamic holy
place.'' An Indian foreign ministry spokesman promptly accused her
of ``malicious meddling'' in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s internal affairs.
   <LOCATION>Saudi Arabia</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Iran</LOCATION> also have criticized the Indian government.
   The dispute has become a chief issue in Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv
Gandhi</PERSON>'s re-election campaign. On <DATE>Saturday</DATE>. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s most
influential Islamic clergyman, <PERSON>Syed Abdullah Bukhari</PERSON>, urged Moslems
to vote <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> out of office.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has more Moslems than any other country in the world
except <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>, even though Indian Moslems form only <PERCENT>11 percent</PERCENT>
of the population of 880 million. They traditionally have voted for
the <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>, so their alienation could prove crucial in the
elections on <DATE>Nov. 22</DATE>, 24 and 26.
   <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> has had a secular government but it has always been headed
by Hindus who make up <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of the population.
</TEXT>
