<HEAD>Hindus Begin Building Temple at Disputed Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With a superficial scratching of earth and
placement of four bricks, Hindu fundamentalists <DATE>Thursday</DATE> reaffirmed
their intention to build a temple that has stirred a religious and
political storm.
   Outnumbered by police and paramilitary troops surrounding the
site, about 2,000 Hindu holy men, politicians, worshipers and
youthful, unarmed guards mobbed a patch of earth considered sacred
by Hindus and Moslems.
   Tens of thousands of other Hindu faithfuls streamed by behind
the ceremony site outside a police barricade. Hindus planned a
formal start to dig the foundation on <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   At least 290 people have died in Hindu-Moslem clashes since
<DATE>August</DATE> when Hindu fundamentalists announced they would build a new
temple to the god Ram on the site of an existing 17th century
mosque.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Vishwa Hindu Parishad</ORGANIZATION>, which is behind the temple program,
maintains the mosque was built atop an ancient Hindu temple marking
the spot where the group says Ram was born 900,000 years ago.
   Most of the deaths occurred late last month in <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION> state, next
to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>'s Uttar Pradesh state, as bricks for the temple were
borne by Hindu processions to this dusty town on the <LOCATION>Saryu River</LOCATION>.
   There have been no reports of deaths in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, and there was
no sign of violence in the town of 35,000 on <DATE>Thursday</DATE>. The <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>
case has become a major campaign issue for Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv
Gandhi</PERSON> as he seeks to return his <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> to power in
elections that will be conducted <DATE>Nov. 22</DATE>, 24 and 26.
   But neither he nor the man trying to replace him, <PERSON>Vishwanath
Pratap Singh</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> coalition, has offered a
solution. They are fearful of alienating the vote of Hindus, who
make up <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 milliion people, although Hindus
traditionally have voted for secular parties. The candidates also
want the Moslem vote, which usually has gone heavily to the
<ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>.
   Singh had planned to visit <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> on <DATE>Thursday</DATE> to cool religious
tensions, but changed his plans and made a short stop in <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>,
about four miles away.
   In <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> said the Hindu-Moslem dispute over the
<LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> site ``cannot be decided by the courts.'' He declined to
say how it should be decided.
   The question of proprietorship at <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> has been dragging
through the courts for four decades.
   So far the only thing legally clear is that the initial
foundation for the new temple is slated for a 25-foot-by-23-foot
plot owned by a Hindu. This tiny plot could hold little more than
the front steps of the proposed temple.
   The rest of the envisoned two-story, three-domed structure would
engulf land whose ownership is under dispute, including the <DATE>17th
century</DATE> mosque.
   ``We will not break down this structure,'' said <PERSON>Ashok Singhal</PERSON>,
referring to the the building Moslems call the Babri Masjid, or
<ORGANIZATION>Mosque of Babar</ORGANIZATION>. Hindus call it the <LOCATION>Ram Janambhoomi</LOCATION>, or <ORGANIZATION>Ram</ORGANIZATION>'s
birthplace.
   ``It can be lifted _ honorably lifted _ and moved, so this
mosque, if it is a mosque, is not destroyed,'' said <PERSON>Singhal</PERSON>, a
senior trustee of the committee to build the new Hindu temple.
   <PERSON>Singhal</PERSON> said he hoped to make such an attempt and begin
contruction within a month, leaving the impression that it would be
deferred until after a new government is chosen.
</TEXT>
