<HEAD>Moslems Protest, Hindus Celebrate Over Shrine Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FAIZABAD, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 1,000 Moslem protesters
<DATE>Friday</DATE> who tried to march to nearby <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, where celebrating
Hindus laid the foundation stone of a new temple at a site claimed
by both religions.
   The Moslem demonstration was peaceful, but <PERSON>Zafaryab Jilani</PERSON>, one
of its leaders, declared: ``When all these methods fail, arms are
taken up. The next generation may not listen to peaceful protest.''
   At least 290 people have been killed in Hindu-Moslem violence in
three Indian states since plans for the temple were announced in
<DATE>August</DATE>. No violence has been reported in <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION> or <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   Protest leaders in <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION> accused Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>
and his <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> of giving in to Hindu fundamentalists in a
quest for Hindu votes in national elections set for <DATE>Nov. 22</DATE>, 24 an
26.
   ``If this ruling <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> is ousted from power, perhaps
secular government can be saved,'' said <PERSON>Jilani</PERSON>, a senior leader of
the <ORGANIZATION>All-India Babri Masjid Action Committee</ORGANIZATION>.
   Babri Masjid, the <ORGANIZATION>Mosque of Babar</ORGANIZATION>, was built in the <DATE>17th century</DATE>
on the spot in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> where Hindu fundamentalists claim one of
their most popular gods, <LOCATION>Lord Ram</LOCATION>, was born.
   About 90 minutes after the arrests in <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>, Hindus
celebrated the laying of the foundation stone of a new Ram temple
130 feet from the <ORGANIZATION>Babar Mosque</ORGANIZATION>. They flung marigold petals into a
6-foot-deep hole in which their leaders reverently placed bricks
and the stone.
   Police wearing helmets and chest protectors struggled to keep
from falling into the pit as at least 5,000 pilgrims pushed into
the small, hilltop enclave in less than an hour.
   The dispute over the <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> hilltop in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh</LOCATION> state is
centuries old and the current chapter began on a night in <DATE>1949</DATE>,
when a Ram idol was spirited into the mosque. A court ordered the
mosque closed to people of both faiths in an effort to prevent
religious strife.
   In <DATE>1986</DATE>, another court order opened the <ORGANIZATION>Babar Mosque</ORGANIZATION>, but only
to Hindus. That decision prompted riots across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> in which at
least 200 people died.
   Currently, the argument centers on who owns the land where the
foundation is being laid. Hindus and Moslems agree the small plot
intended for the stone is owned by a Hindu, but the rest of the
landed needed for the temple remains in dispute.
   Although Moslems opposed construction of the temple, they agreed
they could not prevent the stone from being laid in the plot owned
by a Hindu.
   Late <DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME>, however, Moslem activists contended the
foundation site was spilling over to property they claim is Moslem.
   Courts in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh state</LOCATION>, where <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>
controls the government, have declined to rule who owns the
property.
   ``After today, Moslems will not vote for <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON>Mohammad
Azam Khan</PERSON>, an Uttar Pradesh state legislator from the opposition
<ORGANIZATION>Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, said <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Azam, like <PERSON>Jilani</PERSON>, is a convenor _ a sort of senior organizer _
of the <ORGANIZATION>Babri Masjid Action Committee</ORGANIZATION>. Both were among those
arrested in <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>.
   The arrests were part of a uniquely Indian form of peaceful
protest in which people do something they know police will not
allow, such as marching to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, thus inviting arrest. The
police oblige by rounding them up, generally with little or no
force.
   In <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>, the Moslems and at least 40 Hindu sympathizers
climbed willingly into freight-hauling trucks and waved as they
were driven to a police compound on the outskirts.
   At the compound, they sat on the ground listening to leaders
exhort them to preserve <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> as a secular state and vote <PERSON>Gandhi</PERSON>
and his party out of office.
   Moslems, who make up <PERCENT>11 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people,
have given the <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> strong support since <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s
independence from <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1947</DATE>. Gandhi faces a tough challenge
from <PERSON>Vishwanath Pratap Singh</PERSON>, leader of the <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION>
coalition, and the Moslem vote could be pivotal.
</TEXT>
