<HEAD>Government Proposes Plan to Freeze Hindu-Moslem Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government, trying to defuse a
Hindu-Moslem dispute that has claimed scores of lives, proposed
<DATE>Friday</DATE> to allow Hindus to build a temple at a sacred site without
destroying a mosque already there.
   But Hindu traditionalists rejected the plan, which was unveiled
at the end of a frantic day of meetings and two sessions of Prime
Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>'s Cabinet.
   Singh's government is under threat of collapse if no solution to
the conflict is found by the end of the month.
   The dispute concerns a 16th century mosque in the holy town of
<LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>. Hindus say it was built on the foundations of a temple
over the traditional birthplace of the Hindu god <ORGANIZATION>Rama</ORGANIZATION>.
   A fundamentalist group, the <ORGANIZATION>Hindu World Council</ORGANIZATION>, has vowed to
begin rebuilding the temple on <DATE>Oct. 30</DATE>. Moslems have said they
won't let that happen.
   Officials fear a bloodbath unless a settlement is found. Riots
between the two religious communities have claimed thousands of
lives over the decades, and violence over <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> left more than 80
people dead earlier in the month.
   The secretary of the Hindu group, <PERSON>Ashok Singhal</PERSON>, said the
government plan was unacceptable because it left the mosque in
place.
   The government has said it will not allow the mosque to be
displaced, and has urged all sides to await the decision of the
courts on dozens of petitions.
   Police and paramilitary forces have sealed off <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 300
miles east of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, and about 5,000 Hindu politicians and
activists have been detained.
   Information Minister <PERSON>Parvatheneni Upendra</PERSON> said the prime
minister's plan calls for the government to acquire properties
around the disputed site. Land would be made available for the
construction of a temple, while cases pending before a local court
could be transfered to the <ORGANIZATION>Supreme Court</ORGANIZATION> for quick handling.
Meanwhile, the mosque would stay.
   <PERSON>Upendra</PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata</ORGANIZATION>, a right-wing Hindu party that
is a key government ally, had indicated it might support the prime
minister's plan. But a Bharatiya Janata leader denied that.
   ``It seems the government is more keen to assuage the sentiments
and protect the interests of the Moslem community with disregard to
the sentiments of tens of millions of the overwhelming majority,''
said party secretary <PERSON>J.P. Mathur</PERSON>.
   Lal <PERSON>Krishna Advani</PERSON>, head of Bharatiya Janata, has been leading a
6,000-mile pilgrimage to rally public opinion for the temple. Army
troops were deployed along the route of his caravan.
   Hindus comprise <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people, while
Moslems make up <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of the population.
</TEXT>
