<HEAD>Indian Leader Seeks Peaceful End to Battle Over Religious Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON> on <DATE>Monday</DATE>
appealed for a peaceful resolution to a religious site dispute that
has caused violent Hindu-Moslem clashes and could threaten the
<ORGANIZATION>Singh</ORGANIZATION>'s coalition government.
   ``Religious fanaticism is the first step towards the foundation
for a theocratic state. It will be the death of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> as a secular
state,'' <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> said during a 20-minute televised speech.
   At least 80 people have died this year in battles over a 16th
century mosque, the Babri Masjid, in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, about 310 miles east
of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   Hindus believe the town was the birthplace of a god, <ORGANIZATION>Rama</ORGANIZATION>, and
want to dismantle the mosque, claiming it was built by Mogul rulers
on the foundations of an ancient Hindu temple.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Hindu World Council</ORGANIZATION> has vowed to start rebuilding the temple
<DATE>Oct. 30</DATE>, but a Moslem group had said it will protect the mosque.
Hindus comprise <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people. Moslems
account for <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT>.
   Singh said he has appointed five state chief ministers to help
``solve the issue.'' Chief ministers are the highest elected
officials of a state.
   He also asked the Hindu fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> to
work toward a nonviolent solution.
   There was no immediate reaction from the <LOCATION>Bharatiya Janata</LOCATION>, or
<ORGANIZATION>Indian People's Party</ORGANIZATION>. Several other political parties and groups
have unsuccessfully appealed to the party to call off its campaign.
   Singh's 10-month-old <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> coalition government needs
the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> and the Left Front, a conglomeration of
communist groups, to remain intact.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> has threatened to withdraw support
from the government if the proposed temple construction is
disrupted.
   ``How can a country be governed in circumstances like this? Is
it necessary that the country has to be plunged into communal
chaos? Can't they wait to build the temple until a peaceful
settlement has been reached?'' asked <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>, whose <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal</ORGANIZATION> party
comprises the largest part of the coalition government.
   ``Hundreds of governments can come and go but the nation should
remain one,'' he said. ``Government is too small a consideration
when people are involved.''
   Clashes between the Moslems and Hindus escalated last month
after <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON>Lal Krishna Advani</PERSON> set off on a
6,000-mile van journey from a west Indian Hindu shrine to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   Advani is scheduled to reach <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> on <DATE>Oct. 30</DATE>. Authorities in
<LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh</LOCATION> state have said they may arrest <PERSON>Advani</PERSON> when he
crosses the state border.
   Fearing unrest, police already have detained more than 20,000
Hindu activists. Many road and rail links to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> have been
blocked or subject to stringent checks.
</TEXT>
