<DESCRIPT>  INDIA; RELIGION; MEMORIAL; PAST; CONTROVERSY; MULTIPLE; DEATH  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  For the first time since scores of Hindus were killed last winter when they
battled security forces in this holy Hindu town, hundreds of thousands of
pilgrims traveled peacefully to a shrine here in the last week.;    According
to one district official, more than 1 million Hindus, largely poor, barefoot
and enthusiastic, visited the site March 24, the birthday of the Hindu god
Rama.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  HINDU PILGRIMS FLOCK TO HOLY SITE AFTER DISPUTED
SHRINE REOPENS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The temple, now housed in a 16th-century mosque on a small hill, is
believed by <ORGANIZATION>Rama</ORGANIZATION>'s followers to be his birthplace.;    The site is the center
of a bitter dispute between Hindus and Muslims that led to rioting in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>
last year as Hindu fundamentalists demanded that the mosque be torn down and
replaced with a larger temple.;    The campaign helped topple the minority
government of Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON> and will be a factor in the general
elections in <DATE>May</DATE>. The Muslims say there is no basis for the Hindu belief that
a temple existed at the site before the mosque.;    Negotiations to settle the
issue have stalled, although the tensions of last <DATE>November</DATE> have abated. In
last year's violence, more than 100 people were reportedly killed when they
defied a ban on marches.;    Tight security measures were enforced in the last
week, the first time that the shrine had been opened to the public in such
large numbers since <DATE>last October.</DATE>;    Hundreds of armed troops around the
small, white-washed building searched the pilgrims with metal detectors and
constructed 8- to 10-foot-high barricades of iron pipes topped with barbed
wire.;    Police kept watch through hidden cameras and viewed closed-circuit
television monitors during part of the celebrations.;    The Hindu faith is
embraced by more than 600 million of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s population of 843 million. The
right-wing, nationalist <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, with its espousal of the
temple at <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 300 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, is seeking to convert
those numbers into influence during the general elections.  </TEXT>
