<HEAD>Beleaguered Prime Minister Facing Party Revolt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON> called a
public rally today to try to contain a rebellion in his party and
put a lid on growing pressure on him to resign.
   Environment Minister <PERSON>Maneka Gandhi</PERSON> quit Singh's Cabinet on
<DATE>Friday</DATE> and released a letter accusing the prime minister of failing
to keep his pledge of ``honesty and efficiency in government.''
   <PERSON>Mrs. Gandhi</PERSON> was the first Cabinet minister to break openly with
<PERSON>Singh</PERSON> since <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> when a Hindu-Moslem dispute over rights to a
holy site ballooned into the worst political crisis of the
10-month-old government.
   Other dissidents of the governing <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal</ORGANIZATION> party pressed for a
change of leadership, arguing that dumping Singh could avert the
government's collapse and the need for an immediate national
election.
   Singh was scheduled to speak today at a rally outside his home
in <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, the capital.
   At least 93 people have been killed <DATE>this week</DATE> in rioting between
Moslems and Hindus and in police efforts to quell the disturbances.
The two latest deaths were reported today from a clash between
police and a mob late <DATE>Friday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Ranchi</LOCATION> in the eastern state of
<LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION>.
   Police clamped an overnight curfew on <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, site of the
disputed holy place, and on the neighboring town of <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Friday</DATE>. Thousands of police reinforcements have been sent to the
Hindu holy town 300 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   Hindu fundamentalists have vowed to build a temple at the site
which they say is birthplace of <ORGANIZATION>Lord Rama</ORGANIZATION>, an important Hindu god.
A Moslem mosque has stood there for 460 years.
   Police said they have detained 51,000 people in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh</LOCATION>
state and seized more than 35,000 tribal spears, tridents and other
weapons from Hindus on their way to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   The Uttar Pradesh government has banned entry into the state by
leaders of the Hindu political movements behind the temple project.
   The right-wing <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> withdrew its support for
the government when Singh opposed the temple and arrested the
party's leader, who was on a cross-country march to rouse support
for the construction.
   The party's move deprived the <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> coalition of its
majority in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>.
   Singh faces a no-confidence motion in a special session of the
legislature <DATE>Nov. 7</DATE>. Barring a last-minute compromise or a
realignment of political forces, he seems certain to lose.
   In addition to <PERSON>Mrs. Gandhi</PERSON>, four other <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> members once
considered close to Singh joined the call for him to step down even
before the vote.
</TEXT>
