<HEAD>Police Shoot To Repel Attack On Mosque, 10 Hindus Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to UPDATE with higher death, injury tolls,
quote from injured Hindu. Pickup 10th graf, `Singh's
government...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AYODHYA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fatally shot at least 10 Hindu
fundamentalists today, repulsing a renewed assault on a Moslem
mosque in a religious dispute that has left more than 250 people
dead nationwide.
   More than 60 people and three police officers were injured in
the clash.
   The conflict has spilled into <LOCATION>Moslem Bangladesh</LOCATION>, where two more
people died <DATE>today</DATE> from anti-Hindu rioting. <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION>'s caretaker
prime minister said <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> is not doing enough to protect Moslem
shrines.
   About 10,000 Hindus tried to storm the hilltop <ORGANIZATION>Babri Mosque</ORGANIZATION>,
which they want to replace with a Hindu temple in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 300
miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>. The conflict in the northeastern town
threatens to bring down the government of Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P.
Singh</PERSON>.
   Police used tear gas and pushed back the crowds with blows from
6-foot-long bamboo staves. Reporters saw scores of people injured
before the crowd retreated down dirt alleys and into buildings.
   Police opened fire after coming under a repeated barrage of
stones from the roofs of buildings. Witnesses saw police chasing
the militants onto the roofs and firing on the crowds in the narrow
lanes below.
   Reporters counted 10 bodies in the streets and in a hospital.
Witnesses claimed more people were killed, and Hindu militants
refused to let them take away the corpses.
   Doctors at <ORGANIZATION>Faizabad Hospital</ORGANIZATION> said they treated 64 people for
injuries, including 48 hit by gunfire. Six of those injured were in
critical condition. Three injured policemen were also brought to
the hospital.
   One of the injured Hindus, <PERSON>Bhupendra Singh Rawat</PERSON>, 24, accused
the police of shooting needlessly.
   ``Two policemen dragged a man out of the house and shot him in
the chest. Then they also shot two people who were crying over a
dead body. They were shot in the back,'' he said, speaking from a
hospital bed.
   Today was the last day of a four-day pilgrimage period declared
by astrologers and <PERSON>Hindu</PERSON> holy men as the auspicious time for
beginning construction of the temple.
   At least 257 people have been killed in an unrelenting wave of
violence in six Indian states since the fighting began <DATE>Oct. 24</DATE>,
according to a tally of official reports and news agency accounts.
   Singh's government vowed to defend the Moslem site until the
courts decide its fate. His stand cost him his majority in
<LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> when a Hindu party withdrew its support last week.
   He faces a no-confidence motion <DATE>Nov. 7</DATE>, which he appears likely
to lose. Moves were afoot to replace him as leader of the <ORGANIZATION>Janata
Dal Party</ORGANIZATION>, which might rescue the governing <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION>
coalition from defeat in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>.
   Jockeying in the <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal</ORGANIZATION> centered on two rural-based
politicians, <PERSON>Devi Lal</PERSON> and <PERSON>Chandra Shekhar</PERSON>, who command wide
followings among lower-class Hindus. Singh was elected last year
largely on the strength of the middle class, which grew
disenchanted with the <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> headed by <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>.
   The <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> dispute ignited religious tensions in neighboring
<LOCATION>Bangladesh</LOCATION>, an Islamic nation with a Hindu minority. Three people
were reported killed and more than 350 were wounded in three days
of rioting in <LOCATION>Dhaka</LOCATION>, the capital, and in 12 other cities.
   Doctors said two people died of bullet wounds in <LOCATION>Dhaka</LOCATION> early
today. One Moslem businessman died <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> of wounds suffered in
<LOCATION>Dhaka</LOCATION>.
   Hindus say the 460-year-old Babri Mosque was built on the
foundation of an early Hindu temple marking the birthplace of <ORGANIZATION>Rama</ORGANIZATION>,
the much-worshiped warrior god. Moslems dispute the history of the
site and say that relinquishing the site would jeopardize hundreds
of other Moslem sites.
</TEXT>
