<HEAD>Prime Minister's Party Splits, Capital Paralyzed By Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>'s party broke
apart today, leaving the government in disarray in a country
already seriously shaken by Hindu-Moslem violence that has claimed
more than 330 lives.
   Hindu fundamentalists vowed today to dismantle 3,000 Islamic
shrines across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. They have been thwarted at least temporarily
in their campaign to replace a mosque in the remote northern town
of <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> with a temple.
   The capital, meanwhile, was brought to a near standstill by a
strike called by the right-wing Hindu party that provoked the
political and religious crisis.
   Singh won the endorsement of more than half his <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal
Party</ORGANIZATION>'s members in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, but a large dissident faction
deserted him today and named its own choice for prime minister.
   The dissidents elected <PERSON>Chandra Shekhar</PERSON>, a long-time Singh
antagonist, to lead them and said they would request that President
<PERSON>Ramaswamy Venkataraman</PERSON> ask their new leader to form a government.
   Whatever happens, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> is likely to lose, since he faces a vote
of confidence in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> on <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>.
   The defection from <ORGANIZATION>Singh</ORGANIZATION>'s governing coalition last month of the
Hindu fundamentalist <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, inspired by the arrest
of its leader for instigating unrest in the <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> dispute,
triggered the political crisis.
   In the capital today, Bharatiya Janata activists blocked traffic
by deflating the tires of trucks and buses that ignored their
strike call.
   Many shops were closed. In some areas, private cars and
three-wheel motorscooter taxis were halted.
   Police were deployed on major streets. Most parents kept their
children home from school, fearing trouble.
   Bharatiya Janata was protesting the killings by police of at
least 22 Hindu fundamentalists who were shot last week trying to
replace the <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> mosque with a temple.
   Nationwide, more than 300 othe people have been burned,
stabbed, shot or hacked to death in Hindu-Moslem riots or when
police opened fire to disperse rampaging mobs.
   The position of the beleaguered Singh worsened today with the
resignation of a sixth minister in his 38-member Cabinet.
   Minister of <ORGANIZATION>State for Communications Janeshwar Mishra</ORGANIZATION> submitted
his resignation shortly before <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s showdown with his <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal
Party</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>United News of India</ORGANIZATION> said. The string of desertions began
nearly two weeks ago.
   The daily lurch toward disintegration leaves the entire
government in question. If the <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal</ORGANIZATION> ousts <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>, it's still
questionable whether a new party leader can forge the coalition
support necessary to stay in power. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> could then be headed for
new elections four years ahead of schedule.
   Ayodhya itself, the flashpoint for the sectarian dispute, was
calm <TIME>this morning</TIME>, a day after Hindu leaders suspended their
campaign to seize the mosque after claiming to have reached an
accord with authorities.
   But the stage was set for new confrontations between the Hindu
majority and the Moslem minority when a Hindu fundamentalist leader
vowed to dismantle 3,000 mosques nationwide and replace them with
Hindu temples.
   <PERSON>Ashok Singhal</PERSON>, general secretary of the <ORGANIZATION>World Hindu Council</ORGANIZATION>,
told reporters in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> that his group would beef up its militant
youth wing and expand efforts.
   ``Earlier we wanted three, but now, seeing the government
operation on Hindus, we have decided that we will dismantle 3,000
mosques,'' <PERSON>Singhal</PERSON> said.
   The mosques are those that <PERSON>Singhal</PERSON> and others feel are on Hindu
holy sites. The Hindus want a temple at <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> to honor Ram, the
warrior-god who is one of the most popular Hindu deities.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, which had tacitly supported <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s
government since he took office as prime minister <DATE>Dec. 2, 1989</DATE>, had
fervently supported the temple-building project. Its leader, <PERSON>Lal
Krishna Advani</PERSON>, was arrested <DATE>Oct. 24</DATE> while leading a caravan of
supporters across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   The party promptly withdrew its support, leaving <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> and his
<ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal Party</ORGANIZATION> teetering.
   Today, <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal</ORGANIZATION>'s dissident spokesman <PERSON>Harmohan Dhawan</PERSON> told
reporters that 82 of the the party's 178 members in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>
unanimously chose <PERSON>Chandra Shekhar</PERSON>.
   But Foreign Minister <PERSON>Inder Kumar Gujral</PERSON>, a Singh supporter, said
113 legislators met separately at Parliament and voted unanimously
to support <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>. The figures could not immediately be reconciled.
   Janata Dal was created to unseat former Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv
Gandhi</PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>, which had virtually monopolized
political power in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> since the country won independence from
<LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> in <DATE>1947</DATE>.
   The party was united by little more than anti-Gandhi sentiments,
and the crisis in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> was all it took for ex-Deputy Prime
Minister <PERSON>Devi Lal</PERSON>, a top Singh foe in the party, and others to make
their move.
   Hindus make up <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people, but in
close elections the Moslem minority of <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> is crucial.
</TEXT>
