<HEAD>Governing Party Loses Parliamentary Majority With Key Defection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A right-wing Hindu party deserted Prime
Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>'s coalition <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, depriving the government
of a parliamentary majority. But <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> pledged to hang on to power.
   The walkout was prompted by the arrest <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> of the rightist
party's leader, who had stirred tension between Hindus and Moslems
by campaigning for a new Hindu temple on the site of a Moslem
mosque.
   Singh went on national television to appeal for calm, fearing
the political turmoil arising from a conflict between Hindus and
Moslems could provoke violence.
   ``At this moment, and it is a very tense moment, my heart goes
out to the innocent children, men, women who today are under
tension and under fear,'' he said.
   Initial reports said scattered violence erupted around the
country. <ORGANIZATION>United News of India</ORGANIZATION> said three people were stabbed to
death during rioting in <LOCATION>Ahmedabad</LOCATION> in western <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>.
   At least 80 people died this month in riots between Hindus and
Moslems. They usually were set off by minor squabbles, but were
attributed to the Hindu temple dispute.
   Despite the defection, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> said he was not quitting and will
command enough support to maintain his 10-month-old government when
<ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> reconvenes. Privately, his aides said it was unlikely
the government would complete its four-year term and an early
election was probable next year.
   The legislature is in recess for another three weeks, although
President <PERSON>Ramaswamy Venkataraman</PERSON> has the power to convene it early.
   Venkataraman could let events in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> take their course
when it begins its session next month. He also could ask the
opposition <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>, the largest in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>, to try to
form a new government, or he could call early elections.
   ``The government has been transferred from intensive care to the
terminal ward,'' said <PERSON>V.N. Gadgil</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> spokesman. His
party was ousted in last year's election.
   Officials in <LOCATION>Singh</LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION>Janata Dal Party</ORGANIZATION> said they believed the
Hindu party, the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, would stop short of voting
against the government, since there was no viable alternative.
   The Hindu party's leaders said they would consider rejoining
<PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s coalition if Singh were replaced.
   Singh's minority <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> government relied on the Hindu
party and on the Communist-led Left Front to stay in office.
Neither was formally part of the government.
   The political crisis was prompted by the arrest of the Hindu
party's president, <PERSON>Lal Krishna Advani</PERSON>, during his cross-country
crusade for building a Hindu temple where a mosque now stands in
the Hindu holy town of <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.
   Advani was detained at dawn near the village of Samastipur, 450
miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   Charges against <PERSON>Advani</PERSON> were not published. But up to 20,000 of
his supporters were put under preventative arrest to stop what
authorities feared could become a bloodbath between the two
communities. The Hindu party claimed the figure was closer to
50,000.
   Hindus say the <DATE>16th century</DATE> mosque was built on the ruins of an
earlier temple on the site where the Hindu god <ORGANIZATION>Lord Rama</ORGANIZATION> was born.
A fundamentalist Hindu group says it will begin building a new
temple there <DATE>Oct. 30</DATE>, defying a court injunction.
   Thousands of Moslems and Hindus have died in the long history of
communal bloodshed in the Indian subcontinent. Violence prompted
the partition of colonial <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> into <LOCATION>Moslem Pakistan</LOCATION> and
predominantly <ORGANIZATION>Hindu India</ORGANIZATION> when <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION> granted independence in
<DATE>1947</DATE>.
</TEXT>
