<HEAD>Singh Holds Rally to Contain Rebellion in His Party</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON> called his
supporters to a rally <DATE>Saturday</DATE> as he attempted to contain a
rebellion by party members who want him to resign.
   In a speech to 2,000 loyalists on the lawn of his home, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>
gave no indication he was ready to step down. He pledged his <ORGANIZATION>Janata
Dal</ORGANIZATION> party would champion the downtrodden, as he said it had done
since he took office in <DATE>December</DATE>.
   Environment Minister <PERSON>Maneka Gandhi</PERSON> quit Singh's Cabinet on
<DATE>Friday</DATE>, accusing the prime minister of failing to keep his pledge
of honesty and efficiency. Four Parliament members once considered
close to Singh called on him to step down.
   Singh faces a no-confidence motion in a special session of the
legislature <DATE>Nov. 7</DATE>. Barring a last-minute compromise or a political
realignment, he seems certain to lose.
   Singh has been in trouble since <DATE>Tuesday</DATE>, when a Hindu-Moslem
dispute over rights to a holy site ballooned into the worst
political crisis of the 10-month-old government.
   He was elected largely on the votes of the middle and educated
classes who were disenchanted with the <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION> government led by
<PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>.
   As prime minister, <PERSON>Singh</PERSON> adopted policies aimed at expanding
support with the poor, alienating many of those who put him in
power.
   He also opposed construction of a Hindu temple at <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, where
a Moslem mosque stands. That alienated the right-wing <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya
Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, and without its support <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s coalition no longer
has a majority in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION>.
   At least 93 people died <DATE>last week</DATE> in rioting between Moslems and
Hindus and police efforts to quell the disturbances.
   Police on <DATE>Friday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> clamped a curfew on <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> and on the
neighboring town of <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>.
   Hindu fundamentalists have vowed to build a temple at the site
which they say is birthplace of <ORGANIZATION>Lord Rama</ORGANIZATION>, a Hindu god. However,
the mosque has stood there for 460 years.
   Police said they have detained 51,000 people in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh</LOCATION>
state and seized more than 35,000 tribal spears and other weapons
from Hindus on their way to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 300 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New
Delhi</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
