<HEAD>Police Arrest 163 and Stop Controversial March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested 163 fundamentalist
Hindus on <DATE>Monday</DATE> and stopped them from laying the foundation of a
shrine at a place of worship claimed both by the Hindus and Moslems.
   The disputed site, in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> about 240 miles east of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>,
was the focus of bloody Hindu-Moslem clashes last year.
   Indian news reports said two groups of Hindu devotees were
stopped from going to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> to lay a foundation for a Hindu
temple. The arrests <DATE>Monday</DATE> brought to 313 the number of
fundamentalists detained since <DATE>Saturday</DATE> in the area.
   Bricks for the temple's foundation were also seized, the reports
said. Police also sealed off roads leading to the disputed site.
   Ayodhya was at the center of a controversy between Hindus and
Moslems last year and led to the deaths of about 300 people in
clashes in three states.
   Last <DATE>August</DATE>, Hindu fundamentalists announced they would build a
new temple to their god, Ram, on the site of a <DATE>17th century</DATE> mosque
in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION>Vishwa Hindu Parishad</ORGANIZATION>, which backs the temple
program, maintains the mosque was built atop an ancient Hindu
temple marking the spot where the group says Ram was born 900,000
years ago.
   Most of the deaths occurred in late <DATE>October</DATE> in <LOCATION>Bihar</LOCATION> state, next
to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>'s Uttar Pradesh state, as bricks for the temple were
borne by Hindu processions to the dusty town on the <LOCATION>Saryu River</LOCATION>.
   The controversy, which occurred shortly before national
elections, is thought to have hurt former Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv
Gandhi</PERSON>. Gandhi's <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION> lost the election and was replaced
by Prime Minister <PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>.
   The problems in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> also contributed to worsening ties with
<LOCATION>Moslem Pakistan</LOCATION>. During the troubles last year, <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> Prime
Minister <PERSON>Benazir Bhutto</PERSON> made several statements in support of
<LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s Moslems.
   Relations between the two countries have deteriorated further
because of a bloody separatist campaign in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s state of
<LOCATION>Jammu-Kashmir</LOCATION>. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> accuses <LOCATION>Pakistan</LOCATION> of fomenting the campaign
with arms and training. Pakistan denies the charge and says <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>
is crushing a movement for self-determination.
   Since <DATE>Jan. 20</DATE> when <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> launched a crackdown in <LOCATION>Kashmir</LOCATION>, at
least 349 people have died in the state.
   <PERCENT>Twelve percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people are Moslems and <PERCENT>82
percent</PERCENT> are Hindus.
</TEXT>
