<HEADLINE>
<P>
32 MORE KILLED IN INDIA OVER HINDU CAMPAIGN FOR TEMPLE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW DELHI 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
At least 32 more people were killed <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in religious strife across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> 
over a militant Hindu campaign to build a temple where a mosque now stands, 
domestic news agencies said. 
</P>
<P>
"More blood may spill before there is peace," said <PERSON>Mulayam Singh Yadav</PERSON>, chief 
minister of Uttar Pradesh state, who has organized the defense of the mosque in 
the town of <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>. 
</P>
<P>
Fourteen people were killed <DATE>Thursday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Uttar Pradesh</LOCATION> and seven in <LOCATION>Gujarat</LOCATION>. 
They are two of the states most seriously affected by Hindu-Muslim riots that 
erupted after an abortive attempt <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> by Hindus to raze the mosque. 
</P>
<P>
Dozens of towns across <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> -- an overwhelmingly Hindu land of 850 million 
people with a minority of 100 million Muslims -- were placed under curfew. 
</P>
<P>
"This is pure politics, not religion. Where there is a political problem, there 
can only be a political solution," <PERSON>Yadav</PERSON>, the chief minister of <ORGANIZATION>Uttar Pradesh</ORGANIZATION>, 
said. 
</P>
<P>
At least six people were killed <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, an ancient town of 50,000 
people and 3,000 temples, when militants tried to tear down a 16th-Century 
mosque that is reputed to stand on the birthplace of the Hindu god Ram, hero of 
the epic <ORGANIZATION>Ramayana</ORGANIZATION>. 
</P>
<P>
Hindus say the mosque was built in <DATE>1528</DATE> by <PERSON>Emperor Babur</PERSON> who first demolished a 
temple dedicated to <ORGANIZATION>Ram</ORGANIZATION>. Muslims say they will defend the mosque at any cost. 
</P></TEXT>
