<HEAD>Hindus Break Ground For Temple At Disputed Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   <LOCATION>AYODHYA</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> AP) _ Tens of thousands of militant Hindus stood
guard today with tridents and bows and arrows as priests broke
ground for a temple at a religious site claimed by both Hindus and
Moslems.
   More than 1,000 Hindu pilgrims stood solemnly as four
consecrated bricks passed over their heads and were placed on the
ground as a symbol of the foundation they say they will begin
digging <DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Hundreds of security troops surrounded the disputed shrine,
watched from rooftops and lined the roads leading to <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, a
town of 35,000 people some 325 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   The massive police and paramilitary presence indicated the
lengths the government has taken to prevent violence between
members of the two faiths.
   At least 290 people, mostly Moslems, have been killed in
religious riots across other parts of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> because of plans to
build the temple.
   If ever completed, the temple would engulf a disputed 17th
century shrine claimed by followers of both religions.
   Moslems, who comprise <PERCENT>11 percent</PERCENT> of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880 million people,
say the shrine is the Babri Masjid, or mosque of the Moghal emperor
<PERSON>Babar</PERSON>.
   Hindus, who comprise <PERCENT>82 percent</PERCENT> of the population, claim the
mosque was built over the birthplace of the <ORGANIZATION>Lord Ram</ORGANIZATION>, an
incarnation of <LOCATION>Vishnu</LOCATION>, one of the supreme trinity of gods.
   The dispute over the squat, white buildings with three domes
dates back to the <DATE>19th century</DATE> but erupted afresh in <DATE>August</DATE> after
the militant Vishwa Hindu Parishad, or World Conference of Hindus,
announced plans to build a new temple.
   The ceremony prompted the government to put police and the army
on a state of alert across northern <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. Additional forces were
patrolling cities with significant Moslem populations, including
<LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Home Ministry</ORGANIZATION> officials said on condition of anonymity.
   The issue also has become a focal point for <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s general
elections, scheduled for <DATE>Nov. 22</DATE>, 24 and 26.
   Asked if construction would begin before the elections, <PERSON>Surya
Krishna</PERSON>, joint secretary of the <ORGANIZATION>Vishwa Hindu Parishad</ORGANIZATION>, replied:
``Within a month.''
   Prime Minister <PERSON>Rajiv Gandhi</PERSON>, who faces a strong challenge for
re-election from an opposition coalition, is unwilling to risk
alienating the majority Hindus. He is equally unwilling to risk the
minority Moslem votes, which traditionally have gone in favor of
his <ORGANIZATION>Congress Party</ORGANIZATION>.
   Vishwanah <PERSON>Pratap Singh</PERSON>, leader of the opposition coalition, has
also avoided taking sides on the dispute.
   Both have urged moderation and tolerance by members of both
faiths, without giving any specific suggestions on how to resolve
the problem.
   Singh had planned to be in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> on today to try to keep
tensions from boiling into violence. However, he remained in the
town of <LOCATION>Faizabad</LOCATION>, about four miles away.
   Asked why, he replied, ``This is part of <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>.''
</TEXT>
