<HEAD>Rioting, Police Fire Kill 18; Political Crisis Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 18 people were killed today in
riots and by police nationwide during a strike called by a
right-wing Hindu party that is trying to bring down Prime Minister
<PERSON>V.P. Singh</PERSON>'s government.
   Singh said he will prove on <DATE>Nov. 7</DATE> that he can muster a majority
in <LOCATION>Parliament</LOCATION> despite the defection of the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>.
Whether he can do so is questionable. <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> could soon face new
elections.
   The government called a special one-day session of Parliament on
<DATE>Nov. 7</DATE>. The reports of violence during today's strike came mostly
from small cities and towns in western and southern <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> where
both Hindus and Moslems live.
   The violence and the political crisis were precipitated when <PERSON>Lal
Krishna Advani</PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, was arrested
at sunrise <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> while leading a cross-country caravan to build a
Hindu temple on ground now occupied by a 16th-century Moslem
mosque.
   Five people died <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> night in riots in the western state of
<LOCATION>Gujarat</LOCATION> and police shot to death one person today in <LOCATION>Ahmedabad</LOCATION>, the
state's largest city.
   Another nine people were killed <DATE>today</DATE> in riots and clashes
between police and Hindu demonstrators in <LOCATION>Jaipur</LOCATION>, capital of
<LOCATION>Rajasthan</LOCATION> state that lies between <LOCATION>Gujarat</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>United
News of India</ORGANIZATION> reported.
   One man was stabbed to death and three others died in clashes
and police firing in the southern state of <LOCATION>Karnataka</LOCATION>, Press Trust
of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> said without elaborating. It said two people were killed
in police firing in <LOCATION>West Bengal</LOCATION> state.
   <ORGANIZATION>United News of India</ORGANIZATION> said two people were killed in police
firing in the southern state of <LOCATION>Andhra Pradesh</LOCATION>.
   The news agency described the clashes as ``communal violence,''
a phrase that usually means Hindu-Moslem clashes. Indian news media
routinely avoid giving specific details in such cases, contending
that religious tension would only be heightened.
   Clashes, stone-throwing and arson also were reported in <LOCATION>Bombay</LOCATION>
and other major towns.
   In <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>, many stores were closed and the city government
pulled its 4,000 buses off the streets. Police stepped up patrols
and reported making more than 400 ``preventive arrests.''
   Such arrests are common in <LOCATION>India</LOCATION> where the law permits people to
be held without charge if the authorities believe public safety is
in danger.
   News reports say as many as 50,000 people have been detained in
the last two weeks in potential trouble spots.
   Singh, who took office nearly 11 months ago, told reporters he
would try to prove he has the parliamentary majority he needs to
remain in power.
   In the past, his centrist <ORGANIZATION>National Front</ORGANIZATION> relied on the support
of the <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION> to pass legislation.
   The prime minister said President <PERSON>Ramaswamy Venkataraman</PERSON> had
agreed to call <ORGANIZATION>Parliament</ORGANIZATION> into session ``within a week after <DATE>Oct.
30</DATE>.''
   <DATE>Oct. 30</DATE> is the date set by Hindu holy men and political leaders
to start constructing the temple on the site now occupied by a
mosque in <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION>, 300 miles southeast of <LOCATION>New Delhi</LOCATION>.
   The <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> temple campaign has triggered violence that left
more than 80 people dead in Hindu-Moslem clashes earlier this
month. Singh sought to resolve the mosque-temple dispute in court,
but Hindu fundamentalists pressed ahead with plans to start
building the temple.
   Advani ignored <PERSON>Singh</PERSON>'s pleas to call off his temple campaign. A
few hours after he was arrested, his party withdrew its support for
<ORGANIZATION>Singh</ORGANIZATION>'s government.
   The <ORGANIZATION>Bharatiya Janata Party</ORGANIZATION>, or <ORGANIZATION>Indian People's Party</ORGANIZATION>, proclaims
itself to be a nationalist organization that cannot deny the
``Hindu nature'' of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>. Eighty-two percent of <LOCATION>India</LOCATION>'s 880
million people are Hindus.
   Moslems, who make up <PERCENT>12 percent</PERCENT> of the population, fear the
destruction or relocation of the <LOCATION>Ayodhya</LOCATION> mosque would have a
snowball effect on hundreds of other Moslem sites across the
nation.
</TEXT>
